content.description:
Slab pillar of sorts.  Decent.

Loaded with crystal pockets.
content.location: 1st route right of "Exile on Main Street".

content.description: Flat tech wall.  Sequential crimps and pockets.  Devious and hard for the grade.
content.location: The leftmost of 2 routes on the flat tech wall; the flat tech wall is just left of an obvious dihedral which has "Rez Ryde" in it.

content.description: A fun rompy face climb with some enjoyable and sometimes balancy moves.
content.location: Three 5.9-5.8 routes are located to the right of Chainsaw Willy past a tree.  There is a 5.11 just right of Chainsaw Willy.  They all start near a low pedestal of rock.  The central line is YCK my Dog.

content.description: Tech slab on black rock.  You understand!  Sharp don’t expect chalk, it’s worth figuring it out.  Would be a hard onsite.
content.location: Rightmost of the 4th routes on the small black crag of sorts.

content.description: Ascends the face right of the black streak of Last Trip to Tulsa.  Sustained 5.10a/b all the way to the anchor, mainly crimping up higher.  Well protected and really quite fun, though unfortunately short.
content.location: Right of Uncle Meat, the rightmost of two routes (other is Last Trip to Tulsa) sharing a common anchor that ascend the short wall before it curves into a big corner.

content.description: Route next right to Youth Culture.  Sparse bolting and the moves are really probably only 5.7 but it would be pretty gripping for a 5.7 leader.
content.location: Just right of Youth Culture.  Goes straight up the wall.

content.description: Really nice line with lots of good continuity on nice pockets.   10c is a reasonable grade, but be ready for lots of 10c moves.   It felt harder than the nearby 11a (Screaming Trees).   But at any rate it is a very quality route in a great setting.
content.location: one route to the left of Chainsaw Willy.  Chainsaw is easy to spot because it diagonals up and left from the base, it is a very distinct line.

content.description: Nails hard tech wall.  Very continuous and devious.  Good rock.
content.location: 1st route right left of Exile On Main Street.  Slightly streaked wall.

content.description:
This line has a bouldery start on smallish holds, leading up through the first two bolts.   Then it gets really easy after that (5.8?).

Pretty good line on nice stone, although it is all over after the second bolt.
content.location: one route right of Chainsaw Willy, just on the other side of the tree from Born X-Eyed.

content.description: Proceed straight up to the 3 bolt anchor.  Well protected.  Between the second and fourth bolts is the crux area involving some wicked crossovers.  Doesn't let up much all the way.
content.location: This is the 5th route to the left of Chainsaw Willy. Starts in a little cove of junipers to the left of Alan Shepard Goes to Space.

content.description: Start up slab to corner feature.  Follow crack until it peters out and finally eases onto slab.  Final moves are not straight forward.
content.protection: A handful of bolts to 2 BA missing rings, continue through juggy sharp cap rock to My First Rodeo anchor.
content.location:
Right of Lander Stew.  Start up low angle slab in alcove, right of an alive tree.

Look for a handful of bolted crack routes this is the center  route.

content.description: Obvious dihedral.  Trad sport climbing.  Fun!!!
content.location: Dihedral just to the right of the flat tech wall that houses "Zebra Cakes" and "Beef Pudding".

content.description:
Line of glue ins, through flakes and folds, just left of

Touch of Gray

. Slightly overhanging and pumpy for much of its length.
content.location:
10 feet left of

Touch of Gray

content.description:
last few climbs before Fairfield West starts.  The Doll Face is an obvious overhanging bulge feature.  The bulge has two routes,.12+ and .13b, L to R, then an obvious dihedral to the right and another face which houses "Doll Parts" .11+ and "Our Barbies Ourselves" .12a/b.

Technical start to continous overhang and tech face above.  Good movement!
content.location: the right route on the face to the right of the obvious dihedral feature.

content.description: Just to the right of Touch of Grey . Black streak above some flake features. Cool holds and somewhat continuous.
content.location: First route right of Touch of Grey.

content.description:
Just to the right of Electric Fence. Seam to traverse left to face.   5.11-12 range

Closed project.

A bouldery start to the first bolt, pull a few more moves to a rest on the right.  Proceed up the prow with some interesting 5.10 moves.  Well-protected.

I added another bolt a few years ago so it isn't so led out and replaced the old chain anchor with Fixx rings.
content.location: A short reddish wall on the high point midway between I Wish I was a Catfish and Hellsapoppin.

content.description: It's a bit funky, and a bit harder then it looks! Crimps, a bit of stemming, side pulls, a short finger crack, to a no hands rest, etc. Getting through the finger crack is the crux. Varied climbing - have fun!
content.protection: Bolts, 8-10 draws, hook anchors at the top.
content.location: You start off a big detached flake, and following the seam left of the dead tree located on the wall.

content.description: Easy beginnings to crux after crux and never letting off until you've dropped the rope in the anchor. Great 5.12 cruxes; yeah, that's right: plural! Real for the grade.
content.location: The left most route @ Fairfield Central and the left route on the Doll Face proper.

climbs.name: The Mandate
climbs.fa: Rick Guerrieri, Sandy Flemming, Eric Iwen

content.description: Crux between 2nd and 3rd bolts. Some thin edging and pockets to easier climbing above. Nicely done and well bolted.  A couple of suspect holds that warrant a ginger touch but otherwise enjoyable.
content.location: Just left of Youth Culture Killed my dog at Fairfield Central.

content.description: Steep, pocketed climbing, which gives way to lower-angle rock with good holds and a mantle at the top.
content.protection: Four bolts to drop ins at a communal anchor.
content.location: Starts right of Feminine Intuition and intersects a crack-like feature (FI) at 3/4 height. Look for the steep start with decent pockets.

content.description: Follows a black streak in a sustained 5.8 manner.  Unfortunately short but surprisingly fun.
content.location: Right from Uncle Meat, near where the wall curves into a big corner.  Two routes (Tulsa and Visualize Whirled Peas) meet at the same anchor.

content.description: Follows crack until last two bolts up a face.

climbs.name: Kang Flu
climbs.fa: E: B. Sears; FFA: Griffin Heydt 12/20

content.description:
Technical face/water streak 2 routes right of the obvious roof project.

Equipped by Ben Sears, FA by Griff
content.location: FF Central baby.

content.description: A cruxy start leads to thin climbing, finishing off on larger holds.  Climb has unique style/feel not everyone will appreciate.
content.location: This route starts just right of a large flake, and is the second climb right of a prominent corner.

climbs.name: I Wish I Was a Catfish

content.description: Vertical crimping, fairly sustained to the fourth bolt. Pockets from there to the anchor. Not very obvious what to do in a couple of places: have to be creative.
content.location: A clean, steep wall is encountered a few feet right of Have Mercy. Catfish is the right most route on this wall.

content.description:
Super fun 11. Guidebook rates it 11d, compared to other routes of the same grade at Sinks, this probably could go at 11b/c.

Start in a finger crack in a dihedral laybacking to not too technical face climbing. Get a great nap at a ledge then pull the lip to easy jugs to anchor.

Careful in Fairfield, I've found a good bit of loose rock coming off the climbs here.

One of the older routes, put up in the early 1990's.  At least 3 variations of the opening sequence have been done (right left and center). All three are pretty bouldery, V1-2ish (stick clip #2?). Crimp over another 5.10 section to the third bolt, after which things get easier. Pretty fun stuff and gets your attention.
content.protection: Glue in bolts to drop-in anchor.
content.location: 200-300ft left of Chainsaw Willy.  Picked as reference because it is a unique left trending underling layback there are many climbs in between these routes.  Head left to a defined 90deg corner.  Have Mercy is the 2nd climb left of the defined (offwidth) corner.

content.description: Hard and tricky off the ground.  Black rock with smallish holds.  Par for the wall.
content.protection: Glue ins to drop ins  hard to see
content.location:
The middle of the 3 routes on the small black section of the cliff.

L to R -

Brave Like...

Hanoi Janes'...

World on  a String

content.description:
Be sure to put all of your PPE on for this one!   Stem up a somewhat sharp dihedral before transitioning left onto the face above.

You get extra points if you can do the whole climb without your hands touching your face...or the rock.
content.location:
As you come around the prow just west of the

Beef Pudding

area, this is an obvious left-facing dihedral that starts above a triangle-shaped ramp.

content.description: Fun route with an interesting lay away/pinch crux at the second bolt.  Easier from there to the anchor.  Shares the anchor with Make Peas Great Again.
content.location: Starts as a seam that turns into a right leaning corner between Ancient History and Make Peas Great Again.

content.description: Old school vertical test piece from the Master, Branscomb.  Super good and needs to be appreciated more.  Should be some ticks on it.  Devious and somewhat continuous.
content.location: 1st route right of "Tiger Style".  Also right of burned tree starts in a mini dihedral/arete.  Hard to see glue in bolts.

content.description: Flat pocketed wall that steepens.  Decent climbing up high and fun position.
content.location: To the right of "Hellzapoppin"

content.description: powerful start to pumpy climbing leading towards the dihedral to the left and then back to the anchor up and right.
content.location: left of "Our Barbies...".

content.description: tech face with continuing difficulties and pump factor.
content.location: the right of the two routes on the overhanging wall/face which is to the left of "doll parts" and "our barbies..."

content.description: Project/roof.  Obvious. Suspect 5.12-13 range.
Just to the left of a roof project.  Not sure of the grade.  Slab flake to a corner and ledge. A little dirty.
content.location: 1st route right of an obvious harder roof project.  Painted hangers.

content.description: Flakes and pockets give way to a large rest and a few steep moves guard the chains.
content.location: Just left of a large black streak, this is the fourth climb from the right on an elevated platform.

climbs.name: Chainsaw Willy
climbs.fa: Bob Branscomb, Ed Delong, and B. Sawhill

content.description: A great line with distinct types of climbing.  Some powerful laybacking, a transition from layback to face climbing and intricate face climbing above.  The transition is likely the crux.  A worthy line, with well placed but somewhat spaced bolts.
content.location: See the main description for approach, located about 3/4 the way to the left along the Fairfield Central area.  Starts on a very obvious large left facing layback flake.

content.description: Start on a large leaning flake to clip the first bolt, then make a few tricky moves to big reaches on good pockets and rails.
content.location: Start on top of a large flake that is sunken into the earth at the base of the cliff, with a medium-sized dog cave beneath it.

content.description: Brooklyn Zoo is a short prow route with a couple monos and some good pockets.  Would deserve more stars if it was not so short.  It is worth jumping on if you are climbing all the short routes in this section.
content.protection: 3 bolts(2 glue-in one mechanical) to clip and lowers
content.location: At the right end of the Chainsaw Willy/Uncle Meat area with all the short moderates.  This is the eastern prow route on that wall.

content.description: Tech nasty black rock.  Smallish crockets (crimp pockets).  Bouldery and technical start to tricky exit.
content.location: First route right of "36 Chambers".  First grouping of routes at Farifield Central when you hike up.  Small black section of cliff.  4 routes on this section.

content.description: Tech wall with pockets and cool sequences.
content.location: Just to the right of "Saucerful of Secrets".  In front of the burned juniper tree.

content.description:
Great continuity with lots of 9ish moves.   Nice stone too.

Angles up and left and has some thought provoking sequences.

Recommended!
content.location:
two routes right of Chainsaw Willy, or

one route left of YCKMD

content.description: Begin on a tricky, slightly overhanging start with deep pockets.  Proceed to a lower angle headwall with edges and pockets to a shared anchor.
content.location:
Approximately 15 feet right of a squeeze chimney corner.  Just to the left of

Have Mercy.

content.description: Fun technical corner route.
content.location: Obvious open corner under roof.

content.description: Start up a short lieback to beautiful, copper-colored crimps on velcro-quality rock.  Continues through some standard Fairfield pockets to clip n lowers.  Excellent stone quality and movement.
content.location: This climb is located on the face just left of two prominent dihedrals, just after you come around the corner and up a small incline west of the Beef Pudding wall.  Look for a fat glue in bolt at bolt #1 above a flake buried in the ground.

content.description: Flat tech wall.  The right route of the 2.  Again, sequential and devious pockets.  Good stone.
content.location: Flat tech wall.  The right route of the 2 routes.  First route to the left of "Rez Ryde".

content.description: Start with a few easy moves to a cruxy bouldery sequence that includes an undercling, small crimps and a variety of angled edges. The route transitions to fun pockets, large lock-offs and big moves.
content.protection: 6 bolts plus two bolts for the anchor
content.location: Baby Cakes is located left of Zebra Cakes and to the right of a flake feature that transitions to a thin crack.

content.description: Thin crimps lead to pockets above.
content.location: This is the middle of a small cluster of three routes.

content.description: Sort of a fussy 10a with some high steps and thin moves from the ground to the second bolt.  Some people may want to stick-clip the first bolt. After the second bolt, it becomes substantially easier.
content.location: The next route right of Uncle Meat.  Starts a little higher than the surrounding routes.

content.description: Obvious corner/seam just to the right of the roof project.  Fun climbing up high also.  Fairly sustanied.  Water streak so may get dusty and need some resurrecting.
content.location: Obvious corner/seam just to the right of the roof project.

content.description:
This obscure route apparently sees very little traffic, judging from the absence of chalk and the cobwebs in the pockets.

Nice bouldery moves lead through the first 3 bolts - unfortunately the holds are also quite sharp. So if your tips survive, you then have a bunch of easier climbing on holds that are still pretty sharp.

On the whole, this route has decent enough stone and movement to warrant a star or so, but it isn't likely to be anyone's favorite.  Worth doing if your in the area and your fingertips aren't already ragged.
content.location: one route left of Touch of Gray.  two routes left of Chainsaw Willy

content.description:
Enter the Wu-Tang, or more commonly referred to as "36 Chambers" was Wu-Tang Clan's debut album in 1993 and has since sold over 2 million copies and is regarded as one of the best and most influential hip-hop records of all time.

Much like the album, this route is rugged, raw, and depicts the harsh reality of struggling in New York in the early 90's.

Start on the little block attached to the wall and pull a badass boulder problem off the deck on slightly terrible pockets to a flat undercling. From here, fire up side pulls and pinch pockets out the bulge. It ain't over till' you clip the chains. Living in the world no different from a cell.
content.location: The left most black streak on the first wall you come to in Fairfield Central. Just to the left of Brave like Old John Wayne.
